###Mean

We want the mean of $\hat{p}_\text{A}-\hat{p}_\text{B}$:

$\begin{align}
\mu_{\hat{p}_\text{A}-\hat{p}_\text{B}}&=\blueE{p_\text{A}}-\purpleD{p_\text{B}}
\\\\
&=\blueE{0.60}-\purpleD{0.45}
\\\\
&=0.15
\end{align}$

Intuition check: The population proportions have a difference of $15\%$, so that is the mean or expected difference in the sample proportions.

###Standard deviation

$\begin{align}
\sigma_{\hat{p}_\text{A}-\hat{p}_\text{B}}&=\sqrt{\dfrac{\blueE{p_\text{A}}\left(1-\blueE{p_\text{A}}\right)}{\maroonE{n_\text{A}}}+\dfrac{\purpleD{p_\text{B}}\left(1-\purpleD{p_\text{B}}\right)}{\goldE{n_\text{B}}}}
\\\\
&=\sqrt{\dfrac{\blueE{0.60}\left(1-\blueE{0.60}\right)}{\maroonE{200}}+\dfrac{\purpleD{0.45}\left(1-\purpleD{0.45}\right)}{\goldE{100}}}
\\\\
&=\sqrt{\dfrac{0.60(0.40)}{200}+\dfrac{0.45(0.55)}{100}}
\end{align}$

###Answer

The mean and standard deviation of the sampling distribution of $\hat{p}_\text{A}-\hat{p}_\text{B}$ are:

$\begin{align}
\mu_{\hat{p}_\text{A}-\hat{p}_\text{B}}&=0.15 \\\\
\sigma_{\hat{p}_\text{A}-\hat{p}_\text{B}} &= \sqrt{\dfrac{0.60(0.40)}{200}+\dfrac{0.45(0.55)}{100}}
\end{align}$

